 23: Introducing Class Inheritance
 24: When creating a new class in Java, you can defi ne the class to inherit from an existing class.
 25: Inheritance is the process by which the new child subclass automatically includes any
 26: public or protected primitives, objects, or methods defi ned in the parent class.
 27: For illustrative purposes, we refer to any class that inherits from another class as a child
 28: class, or a descendent of that class. Alternatively, we refer to the class that the child inherits
 29: from as the parent class, or an ancestor of the class. If child X inherits from class Y, which
 30: in turn inherits from class Z, then X would be considered an indirect child, or descendent,
 31: of class Z.
 32: Java supports single inheritance, by which a class may inherit from only one direct par-
 33: ent class. Java also supports multiple levels of inheritance, by which one class may extend
 34: another class, which in turn extends another class. You can extend a class any number of
 35: times, allowing each descendent to gain access to its ancestor’s members.
 36: To truly understand single inheritance, it may helpful to contrast it with multiple inheri-
 37: tance, by which a class may have multiple direct parents. By design, Java doesn’t support
 38: multiple inheritance in the language because studies have shown that multiple inheritance
 39: can lead to complex, often difficult-to-maintain code. Java does allow one exception to the
 40: single inheritance rule: classes may implement multiple interfaces, as you’ll see later in this
 41: chapter.
 42: Figure 5.1 illustrates the various types of inheritance models. The items on the left are
 43: considered single inheritance because each child has exactly one parent. You may notice
 44: that single inheritance doesn’t preclude parents from having multiple children. The right
 45: Introducing Class Inheritance                       235
 46: side shows items that have multiple inheritance. For example, a dog object has multiple par-
 47: ent designations. Part of what makes multiple inheritance complicated is determining which
 48: parent to inherit values from in case of a confl ict. For example, if you have an object or
 49: method defi ned in all of the parents, which one does the child inherit? There is no natural
 50: ordering for parents in this example, which is why Java avoids these issues by disallowing
 51: multiple inheritance altogether.
